	description={`Bible verses and encouragement for nurses, free with audio. You carry others through their worst days — meet the Father who carries you, so you nurse from overflow.`}
	h1={`The Bible for Nurses`}
	heroEyebrow={`A Father For`}
	heroSubhead={`You hold so many people through the hardest moments of their lives — the long shifts, the codes, the families in the waiting room, the patient who didn't make it. But who holds you? Here is the truth underneath the exhaustion: you have a Father in heaven who tends the caregiver, so you can pour out from the overflow of being held, not the edge of empty.`}
	heroBase={`https://cdn.sanity.io/images/rusi1hyi/production/6dc31c86e6218eb1872b07819100f2c1b12a9adb-1100x825.jpg`}
	heroAlt={`A nurse in scrubs holding a stethoscope, smiling in a hospital corridor`}
	heroObjectPosition={`center top`}
	directAnswerHtml={`<strong style="color: var(--color-ink);">If you're a nurse, the Father's Heart Bible™ is for you.</strong> You carry what most people never see — the back-to-back shifts, the understaffing, the suffering you can't un-witness, the running on empty while everyone leans on you. The <a href="https://fathersheartbible.com/read" style="color: var(--color-brand);" class="hover:underline">Father's Heart Bible™</a> is a fresh English translation you can read and <em>listen to</em> free on your phone — and it reveals God as a <em>Father</em> from beginning to end. Whether you searched "Bible verses for nurses," "encouragement for nurses," or "scripture for healthcare workers" — the answer starts in one place: before you are the one who carries everyone else, you are a beloved child your Father carries. You nurse from the overflow of being held, not the edge of empty.`}
	keyTakeaway={`You are not loved because of how much you give or how many shifts you survive. Before you ever care for another patient, you are the Father's beloved child — fathered first, held first, so you pour out from overflow instead of from an empty tank.`}
	painsHeading={`The weight nurses carry`}
	painsIntroHtml={`If you feel burned out, depleted, or like you have nothing left to give, you are not weak and you are not alone. An entire profession is carrying the same weight — and the numbers say it out loud.`}
	painStats={[
		{ value: `56%`, label: `of nurses reported experiencing symptoms of burnout (AMN Healthcare, 2023)` },
		{ value: `64%`, label: `of nurses say they feel a great deal of stress because of their job (AMN Healthcare, 2023)` },
		{ value: `100,000`, label: `registered nurses left the workforce during the pandemic — the largest drop in 40 years (NCSBN, 2023)` },
		{ value: `610,000`, label: `RNs reported an intent to leave the workforce by 2027 due to stress, burnout, and retirement (NCSBN, 2023)` },
		{ value: `31%`, label: `of nurses who left their job cited burnout or a stressful work environment as the reason (NSI Nursing Solutions, 2023)` },
		{ value: `45%`, label: `of inpatient nurses said they were likely to leave their role within six months (McKinsey, 2023)` },
	]}
	painsBodyHtml={`<p>Behind every statistic is a real nurse — maybe you. The shift that ran three hours long because there was no one to relieve you. The patient you couldn't save, carried home in your chest. The compassion fatigue that creeps in when you've absorbed too much suffering with no space to process it. The moral injury of knowing what good care looks like and not having the staff or time to give it.</p><p>None of this means something is wrong with you. It means you're human, doing one of the most sacred and depleting jobs there is — holding others through their worst days while rarely being held yourself. There is a Father who tends the caregiver, and He has something to say about who carries <em>you</em>.</p>`}
	painsSources={[
		{ label: `NCSBN — Research Projects Significant Nursing Workforce Shortages and Crisis`, url: `https://www.ncsbn.org/news/ncsbn-research-projects-significant-nursing-workforce-shortages-and-crisis` },
		{ label: `AMN Healthcare — Survey of Registered Nurses`, url: `https://www.amnhealthcare.com/amn-insights/nursing/surveys/2023-survey-of-registered-nurses/` },
		{ label: `McKinsey — Nursing in 2023: How hospitals are confronting shortages`, url: `https://www.mckinsey.com/industries/healthcare/our-insights/nursing-in-2023` },
	]}
	aFatherHeading={`A Father for nurses`}
	aFatherBodyHtml={`<p>Here's what almost no one tells you in the middle of a brutal stretch of shifts: the answer to burnout isn't more grit, a better self-care routine, or finally learning to give from an even emptier tank. The answer is a <strong style="color: var(--color-ink);">Father</strong> — a perfect, holy Father who already loves you, today, before you do a single thing for anyone else.</p><p>You were not made to be an endless source of care that never gets refilled. You were made to be a beloved child first — fathered, tended, held. And the One who made you doesn't measure your worth by how much you pour out or how many patients you carry. He calls you His beloved son, His beloved daughter — not the tireless caregiver version of you, but <em>you</em>, right now, depleted and human.</p><p>So before you're a nurse, a caregiver, the one everyone leans on — you are His. Your heavenly Father wants to be the One who carries you, so that what flows out of you to your patients comes from overflow, not from the scraping bottom of empty. He says: I see you, I'm proud of you, now come and let Me hold you.</p>`}
